# GitHub Issue Workflow

When taking a GitHub issue, follow this workflow strictly.

## 1. Branch Creation

Always branch from the latest `main`:

```bash
git checkout main
git pull origin main
git checkout -b <type>/<issue-number>-<short-description>
```

### Branch Prefixes

| Prefix      | When to use                          |
|-------------|--------------------------------------|
| `feature/`  | New functionality                    |
| `bugfix/`   | Bug fixes                            |
| `hotfix/`   | Urgent production fixes              |
| `chore/`    | Maintenance, tooling, CI changes     |
| `refactor/` | Code restructuring, no behavior change |
| `docs/`     | Documentation only                   |
| `test/`     | Adding or fixing tests               |

### Branch Name Rules

- Use **kebab-case** for the short description.
- Keep it concise (3-5 words max).
- Always include the issue number.

**Examples:**

- `feature/42-add-user-profile`
- `bugfix/108-fix-login-timeout`
- `hotfix/7-null-ref-on-startup`
- `refactor/55-extract-order-service`

## 2. Commits — Conventional Commits

Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) spec:

```
<type>(optional-scope): <description>
```

- `feat:` — new feature (maps to SemVer minor)
- `fix:` — bug fix (maps to SemVer patch)
- `refactor:` — restructure without behavior change
- `chore:` — tooling, deps, CI
- `docs:` — documentation only
- `test:` — adding or updating tests

**Examples:**

- `feat(auth): add JWT token refresh`
- `fix: resolve null reference in OrderService`
- `test: add unit tests for CartService`

## 3. Pre-PR Checks

Before creating the PR, review whether `.cursor/rules/project-context.mdc` needs updating per its maintenance rules (new files, renamed modules, new commands, changed flows).

## 4. Self Code Review

Before pushing and creating the PR, perform a self code review on **all files changed in this branch**. Use `git diff main...HEAD` to identify the changed files, then review each one.

### What to check

| Category | Look for |
|---|---|
| **Bugs & logic errors** | Off-by-one errors, wrong conditions, missing edge cases, incorrect return values |
| **Error handling** | Swallowed errors, overly broad catches, missing error handling on async calls |
| **Resource management** | Disposables not cleaned up, event listeners not unsubscribed, missing `finally` blocks |
| **Race conditions** | Unguarded shared state, missing cancellation checks, async operations that can interleave |
| **Naming & readability** | Unclear names, misleading names, inconsistent conventions |
| **Dead code** | Unused imports, unreachable branches, leftover debugging code |
| **Security** | Hardcoded secrets, unsanitized input passed to shells or file paths |
| **Performance** | Unnecessary allocations in hot paths, redundant iterations, missing early returns |
| **API misuse** | Incorrect use of VS Code API, Node.js API, or third-party library APIs |
| **Duplication** | Copy-pasted logic that should be extracted into a shared helper |

### Procedure

1. Read every changed file.
2. For each issue found, fix it immediately.
3. After fixing, re-run linting (`ReadLints`) on the affected files.
4. If fixes were needed, create a new commit: `chore: self-review fixes`.
5. If no issues are found, proceed — do not mention the review to the user unless problems were found and fixed.

## 5. Pull Request

When done working on an issue, **automatically create a pull request** — do not wait for the user to ask.

- Push the branch and create a PR to `main` using `gh pr create`.
- PR title should follow Conventional Commits format.
- Reference the issue using a closing keyword: `Closes #<issue-number>`.
- Use this PR body template:

```
## Summary
<1-3 bullet points describing what changed and why>

Closes #<issue-number>

## Test plan
- [ ] <specific verification steps>
```
